1
00:00:05,600 --> 00:00:06,480
Hello, everyone.

2
00:00:06,480 --> 00:00:11,600
And again, welcome to
lecture 6 of CME 295.

3
00:00:11,600 --> 00:00:13,760
So today is actually
an exciting day

4
00:00:13,760 --> 00:00:16,720
because we're going
to cover a topic that

5
00:00:16,720 --> 00:00:18,960
has been trending
over the past year

6
00:00:18,960 --> 00:00:23,440
or so which is LLM reasoning.

7
00:00:23,440 --> 00:00:25,440
And it's actually a
good segue compared

8
00:00:25,440 --> 00:00:28,160
to what we talked
last time, which

9
00:00:28,160 --> 00:00:32,880
was preference tuning, because a
lot of the methods that we used

10
00:00:32,880 --> 00:00:35,680
in lecture 5 are going
to be the ones that we'll

11
00:00:35,680 --> 00:00:40,960
be using as the foundations
for this lecture.

12
00:00:40,960 --> 00:00:44,000
So before we start,
as usual, we're

13
00:00:44,000 --> 00:00:49,440
going to just cover quickly
what we saw in the last lecture.

14
00:00:49,440 --> 00:00:54,240
So if you remember,
lecture 4 and lecture 5

15
00:00:54,240 --> 00:00:58,640
were all about learning
how we can train a model.

16
00:00:58,640 --> 00:01:02,800
So in lecture 4, we
saw the first part,

17
00:01:02,800 --> 00:01:05,360
which was the
pre-training part, which

18
00:01:05,360 --> 00:01:10,640
is the most compute-intensive
step where we basically

19
00:01:10,640 --> 00:01:16,160
teach the model the structure
of text, the structure of codes.

20
00:01:16,160 --> 00:01:20,960
And we do this very large,
large scale training.

21
00:01:20,960 --> 00:01:23,920
So at the end of this first
step, which is pre-training,

22
00:01:23,920 --> 00:01:29,120
we get a model that knows about
code, that knows about language,

23
00:01:29,120 --> 00:01:34,160
but it only knows how to
autocomplete a sequence.

24
00:01:34,160 --> 00:01:37,600
And so that's why we also
saw the second step, which

25
00:01:37,600 --> 00:01:43,360
was the fine tuning step where
we take our pre-trained model

26
00:01:43,360 --> 00:01:46,240
and we try to make it useful.

27
00:01:46,240 --> 00:01:50,720
So one use case that we saw
was for instance, an assistant.

28
00:01:50,720 --> 00:01:53,680
So we tried to tune
it in a way that it

29
00:01:53,680 --> 00:01:56,000
can respond to questions.

30
00:01:56,000 --> 00:02:02,320
And so here, we have this work
of preparing the SFT data, which

31
00:02:02,320 --> 00:02:07,200
is what we call the SFT data,
which is a high quality,

32
00:02:07,200 --> 00:02:11,280
curated data set that we can
use to teach our model on how

33
00:02:11,280 --> 00:02:12,800
to behave.

34
00:02:12,800 --> 00:02:14,720
So at the end of
this second step,

35
00:02:14,720 --> 00:02:19,360
we have our model that is tuned
for a specific task, which

36
00:02:19,360 --> 00:02:22,880
can be responding to queries.

37
00:02:22,880 --> 00:02:28,480
And then last lecture, we
saw this third step, which

38
00:02:28,480 --> 00:02:30,880
was the preference tuning step.

39
00:02:30,880 --> 00:02:35,280
And here the goal is
to align our model

40
00:02:35,280 --> 00:02:38,240
with human preferences.

41
00:02:38,240 --> 00:02:41,920
So we saw, in
particular, RLHF, which

42
00:02:41,920 --> 00:02:45,120
was a common method to do that.

43
00:02:45,120 --> 00:02:47,440
And we saw that there
was two steps to it.

44
00:02:47,440 --> 00:02:50,960
So there was the
first part, learning

45
00:02:50,960 --> 00:02:57,200
to distinguish good from bad
using human preference data,

46
00:02:57,200 --> 00:02:59,440
and then there was
this second step,

47
00:02:59,440 --> 00:03:04,400
which was this RL stage, which
is going to be useful today.

48
00:03:05,120 --> 00:03:07,760
So in particular,
if you remember,

49
00:03:07,760 --> 00:03:12,560
we had drawn a comparison
between the RL setup

50
00:03:12,560 --> 00:03:16,960
that you may be familiar
with outside of this class,

51
00:03:16,960 --> 00:03:20,960
where we have an agent
that is interacting

52
00:03:20,960 --> 00:03:25,840
with the environment and the
way that it interacts with it,

53
00:03:25,840 --> 00:03:31,520
is that given a
state that it is in,

54
00:03:31,520 --> 00:03:36,480
it can take an action
following a policy, which

55
00:03:36,480 --> 00:03:39,120
is nothing else than
just a probability

56
00:03:39,120 --> 00:03:41,840
distribution over actions.

57
00:03:41,840 --> 00:03:48,080
So given a state, our
agent can take an action

58
00:03:48,080 --> 00:03:49,680
following this policy.

59
00:03:49,680 --> 00:03:55,280
And at the result of this,
it receives some reward.

60
00:03:55,280 --> 00:03:58,240
And we saw last
lecture that we have

61
00:03:58,240 --> 00:04:04,080
this nice comparison between the
traditional RL setup and the LLM

62
00:04:04,080 --> 00:04:05,200
setup.

63
00:04:05,200 --> 00:04:10,240
And so here, our, quote unquote,
agents is just simply the LLM.

64
00:04:11,280 --> 00:04:13,680
The environment that
it interacts with

65
00:04:13,680 --> 00:04:18,000
is just a set of tokens
that it can predict over.

66
00:04:18,000 --> 00:04:24,160
So given an input that
it has received so far,

67
00:04:24,160 --> 00:04:27,600
it can predict what the
next token could be,

68
00:04:27,600 --> 00:04:29,360
which is the action.

69
00:04:29,360 --> 00:04:34,480
And it does that using the
probability distribution that

70
00:04:34,480 --> 00:04:39,280
is the result of, I
guess, the LLM prediction.

71
00:04:39,280 --> 00:04:45,360
And we saw that we can
obtain human preferences

72
00:04:45,360 --> 00:04:49,440
for each completion.

73
00:04:49,440 --> 00:04:52,880
So you have a prompt,
you have a completion,

74
00:04:52,880 --> 00:04:56,240
and you get those
human preferences.

75
00:04:56,240 --> 00:04:58,000
And this is the
one that you then

76
00:04:58,000 --> 00:05:02,480
use in order to tune the LLM.

77
00:05:02,480 --> 00:05:07,280
Because here, this step is
about aligning the model

78
00:05:07,280 --> 00:05:08,720
with human preferences.

79
00:05:08,720 --> 00:05:13,600
And here, the human preferences
is encapsulated in the reward.

80
00:05:13,600 --> 00:05:18,080
And so we saw that the loss
function during the RL stage

81
00:05:18,080 --> 00:05:20,560
is composed of two parts.

82
00:05:21,360 --> 00:05:27,040
So the first part is this
advantage maximization.

83
00:05:27,040 --> 00:05:32,480
And we saw that that advantage
was based on the rewards.

84
00:05:32,480 --> 00:05:36,320
And it has some
baseline to just reduce

85
00:05:36,320 --> 00:05:39,760
the variance of the gradient.

86
00:05:39,760 --> 00:05:40,960
So we have that part.

87
00:05:40,960 --> 00:05:45,760
But we also saw
another part, which

88
00:05:45,760 --> 00:05:48,960
was that we don't want
our model to deviate

89
00:05:48,960 --> 00:05:54,080
too much from either
the previous iteration--

90
00:05:54,080 --> 00:05:57,040
so we don't want the model to
change too much from iteration

91
00:05:57,040 --> 00:05:59,040
to iteration--

92
00:05:59,040 --> 00:06:02,560
but we also don't want our model
to change too much compared

93
00:06:02,560 --> 00:06:06,480
to our initial model,
like our base model.

94
00:06:06,480 --> 00:06:09,120
And here, it's the SFT model.

95
00:06:09,120 --> 00:06:12,960
And the reason why we don't
want to change too much

96
00:06:12,960 --> 00:06:17,280
is because our model has
already learned a lot.

97
00:06:17,280 --> 00:06:21,360
It's already quite
performant in what it does.

98
00:06:21,360 --> 00:06:23,760
And what we want
is to just align it

99
00:06:23,760 --> 00:06:27,360
with human preferences, which is
not something for which we want

100
00:06:27,360 --> 00:06:30,560
the model to change completely.

101
00:06:30,560 --> 00:06:33,200
And I think that
was the part that I

102
00:06:33,200 --> 00:06:35,760
think was a little bit scary,
which was the actual loss

103
00:06:35,760 --> 00:06:37,120
functions.

104
00:06:37,120 --> 00:06:40,240
So if you remember,
the main algorithm

105
00:06:40,240 --> 00:06:43,440
that is typically used
in the RLHF setting

106
00:06:43,440 --> 00:06:49,120
is PPO, which stands for
proximal policy optimization.

107
00:06:49,120 --> 00:06:50,960
And there is this
one variant that's

108
00:06:50,960 --> 00:07:00,320
called PPO CLIP, which is
such that it clips the updates

109
00:07:00,320 --> 00:07:03,360
from one iteration to another.

110
00:07:03,360 --> 00:07:07,760
So here, if you remember, R
is actually not the reward,

111
00:07:07,760 --> 00:07:09,040
it is the ratio.

112
00:07:09,040 --> 00:07:13,360
And it's a confusing notation.

113
00:07:13,360 --> 00:07:17,280
So it's the ratio between
the current policy

114
00:07:17,280 --> 00:07:19,280
and the old policy.

115
00:07:19,280 --> 00:07:22,240
And the old policy
here is the policy

116
00:07:22,240 --> 00:07:26,480
that is at the
previous RL iteration.

117
00:07:26,480 --> 00:07:30,800
So what we do is that we have
a clipping mechanism such that

118
00:07:30,800 --> 00:07:36,320
the ratio cannot go beyond
some certain thresholds,

119
00:07:36,320 --> 00:07:40,640
such that we do not want to
incentivize the model to make

120
00:07:40,640 --> 00:07:44,000
too big of an update.

121
00:07:44,000 --> 00:07:47,360
And we saw another
variant of PPO

122
00:07:47,360 --> 00:07:51,600
which is called PPO-KL penalty.

123
00:07:51,600 --> 00:07:58,800
And this variant uses the KL
divergence to penalize the model

124
00:07:58,800 --> 00:08:01,920
from changing too much.

125
00:08:01,920 --> 00:08:05,280
So if you remember in
the original PPO paper,

126
00:08:06,160 --> 00:08:10,560
we used the old, quote
unquote, old version

127
00:08:10,560 --> 00:08:14,400
of the model, which is the one
that the previous RL iteration.

128
00:08:14,400 --> 00:08:20,160
But in modern day RLHF
training, this KL divergence

129
00:08:20,160 --> 00:08:25,200
is typically applied to the base
model, which is the SFT model.

130
00:08:25,200 --> 00:08:30,000
So I guess long story short
is we have these two PPO

131
00:08:30,000 --> 00:08:33,280
variants that were variants
that were introduced

132
00:08:33,280 --> 00:08:36,400
in the original PPO paper.

133
00:08:36,400 --> 00:08:40,560
But in modern day RLHF
training, we typically

134
00:08:40,560 --> 00:08:50,480
have some combination, some mix
of these two loss functions.

135
00:08:50,480 --> 00:08:51,280
Cool?

136
00:08:51,840 --> 00:08:55,360
So up until now,
we've seen what I

137
00:08:55,360 --> 00:09:00,320
want to call vanilla LLMs, which
are LLMs that take something

138
00:09:00,320 --> 00:09:03,680
as an input, let's
say a prompt, and just

139
00:09:03,680 --> 00:09:06,400
respond with some answer.

140
00:09:06,400 --> 00:09:10,160
And so those vanilla LLMs,
they have a lot of strength

141
00:09:10,160 --> 00:09:11,600
that you can enjoy.

142
00:09:11,600 --> 00:09:15,120
So first of all, we had
seen that those LLMs,

143
00:09:15,120 --> 00:09:17,440
they know a lot about
structure, of the text,

144
00:09:17,440 --> 00:09:19,440
they know a lot about codes.

145
00:09:19,440 --> 00:09:22,560
So in particular, if you
want to debug your code,

146
00:09:22,560 --> 00:09:25,680
I guess they are great to
find where the error is.

147
00:09:25,680 --> 00:09:28,080
They are great to
generate codes.

148
00:09:28,080 --> 00:09:31,920
They're also great to
generate essays or poems.

149
00:09:31,920 --> 00:09:34,800
They're really,
really good at that.

150
00:09:34,800 --> 00:09:38,720
But I do want to call
out some weaknesses.

151
00:09:38,720 --> 00:09:41,200
So the first, I
guess, weakness that I

152
00:09:41,200 --> 00:09:44,080
want to call out in
this vanilla LLMs

153
00:09:44,080 --> 00:09:48,480
is that they have, quote
unquote, limited reasoning.

154
00:09:49,360 --> 00:09:54,640
So typically, if you have
some sophisticated, let's say,

155
00:09:54,640 --> 00:10:01,440
math problem, it will
not really come up with,

156
00:10:01,440 --> 00:10:05,200
I guess, the solution
because maybe it will get

157
00:10:05,200 --> 00:10:09,280
lost in the way
because up until now,

158
00:10:09,280 --> 00:10:11,840
our model has been
really trained to,

159
00:10:11,840 --> 00:10:15,840
I guess, given a prompt,
respond to it using

160
00:10:15,840 --> 00:10:17,680
the next token prediction.

161
00:10:18,400 --> 00:10:20,960
So I guess here, there is
not really a big reason

162
00:10:20,960 --> 00:10:26,000
why it would be able to
solve complicated problems.

163
00:10:26,000 --> 00:10:28,640
So I guess that is one.

164
00:10:28,640 --> 00:10:34,080
So second weakness is
that the LLM that we have

165
00:10:34,080 --> 00:10:40,080
has been pre-trained on a huge
amount of data, which is static,

166
00:10:40,080 --> 00:10:44,000
meaning that the knowledge
that the LLM has acquired

167
00:10:44,000 --> 00:10:46,880
is bound to the cutoff date,
what we call the cutoff

168
00:10:46,880 --> 00:10:53,760
date, at which we cut and
formed our pre-training data.

169
00:10:53,760 --> 00:10:58,160
So I know a few days
ago, we had an election.

170
00:10:58,160 --> 00:11:02,160
So if, let's say, we trained
our LLM based on data

171
00:11:02,160 --> 00:11:03,920
before the election
and let's say today,

172
00:11:03,920 --> 00:11:05,760
we ask it, who is the--

173
00:11:05,760 --> 00:11:08,960
I don't know-- elected
official of let's say X,

174
00:11:08,960 --> 00:11:13,280
it will not be able to answer us
because it does not have access

175
00:11:13,280 --> 00:11:17,120
to knowledge after that date.

176
00:11:17,120 --> 00:11:22,880
So a third weakness is so
far, it's all talk, no action.

177
00:11:22,880 --> 00:11:24,880
So you just prompt your LLM.

178
00:11:24,880 --> 00:11:26,560
But I guess if you
want to let's say,

179
00:11:26,560 --> 00:11:32,720
I don't know, place an order
or don't do some action,

180
00:11:32,720 --> 00:11:35,760
you just kind of do it.

181
00:11:35,760 --> 00:11:38,320
And then I guess the last
weakness, which by the way,

182
00:11:38,320 --> 00:11:43,520
is not an exhaustive list, is
contrary to traditional NLP

183
00:11:43,520 --> 00:11:48,880
models LLMs, they
generate free form texts.

184
00:11:48,880 --> 00:11:53,600
And it's hard to evaluate them
in the framework that we--

185
00:11:53,600 --> 00:11:57,440
I mean, by we is the ML
community has adopted up

186
00:11:57,440 --> 00:11:59,600
until a few years ago.

187
00:11:59,600 --> 00:12:01,600
So if you're familiar
with it, let's suppose

188
00:12:01,600 --> 00:12:04,240
if you worked in the
translation world,

189
00:12:04,240 --> 00:12:09,680
you would use rule-based metrics
like BLEU or for summarization,

190
00:12:09,680 --> 00:12:12,720
ROUGE to evaluate your output.

191
00:12:12,720 --> 00:12:17,120
But then here, LLMs, they can
really do more than just that.

192
00:12:17,120 --> 00:12:20,800
So it's very hard
to evaluate them.

193
00:12:20,800 --> 00:12:24,400
So what I want to
say is that this

194
00:12:24,400 --> 00:12:26,640
is, let's say, a subset
of all the weaknesses

195
00:12:26,640 --> 00:12:28,560
that LLMs can have.

196
00:12:28,560 --> 00:12:31,920
And the last three
are going to be topics

197
00:12:31,920 --> 00:12:36,960
that we'll cover in the next
lecture and in the lecture 8.

198
00:12:36,960 --> 00:12:42,320
And as I mentioned before, the
focus of today is reasoning.

199
00:12:42,320 --> 00:12:48,880
So we'll see how we can improve
the way our LLM reasons.

200
00:12:48,880 --> 00:12:50,080
Cool.

201
00:12:50,080 --> 00:12:54,400
And again, this is a topic
that's been very new.

202
00:12:54,400 --> 00:12:57,280
And by new, I mean
roughly a year.

203
00:12:57,280 --> 00:12:59,760
So almost everything
that we will see

204
00:12:59,760 --> 00:13:04,080
is either from 2024 or 2025.

205
00:13:04,080 --> 00:13:08,400
And I guess we're lucky
because now we have enough

206
00:13:08,400 --> 00:13:11,280
hindsight to just know
which piece is more

207
00:13:11,280 --> 00:13:13,120
important than other things.

208
00:13:13,120 --> 00:13:15,680
And so the goal
for today is going

209
00:13:15,680 --> 00:13:20,720
to be to know what
reasoning models are.

210
00:13:20,720 --> 00:13:24,560
And the second big goal is
to how they are trained.

211
00:13:25,200 --> 00:13:27,920
So hopefully, at the
end of this lecture,

212
00:13:27,920 --> 00:13:31,040
if you have a good answer
to these two questions,

213
00:13:31,040 --> 00:13:35,280
that means that we
have done a good job.

214
00:13:35,280 --> 00:13:37,680
So let's start with
reasoning models.

215
00:13:37,680 --> 00:13:39,440
What are they?

216
00:13:39,440 --> 00:13:44,480
Well, to answer this question,
we first need to, I guess,

217
00:13:44,480 --> 00:13:47,520
define what reasoning is.

218
00:13:47,520 --> 00:13:50,240
And the bad news
here is there's not

219
00:13:50,240 --> 00:13:53,280
a commonly agreed
upon definition

220
00:13:53,280 --> 00:13:55,280
out there of what reasoning is.

221
00:13:55,280 --> 00:13:59,520
So I will try to
define it, I guess,

222
00:13:59,520 --> 00:14:01,440
to the best of my ability.

223
00:14:01,440 --> 00:14:08,640
So here, we define reasoning as
the ability to solve a problem.

224
00:14:08,640 --> 00:14:10,960
And here, by
problem, we typically

225
00:14:10,960 --> 00:14:16,560
think more of math problems
or, let's say, coding problems.

226
00:14:17,200 --> 00:14:22,320
But hopefully, these abilities
can also spread to other fields

227
00:14:22,320 --> 00:14:24,480
as well.

228
00:14:24,480 --> 00:14:29,120
And in order to
solve this problem,

229
00:14:29,120 --> 00:14:34,160
we typically need a
multi-step reasoning process,

230
00:14:34,160 --> 00:14:36,400
a little bit like
when you take an exam,

231
00:14:36,400 --> 00:14:39,840
when you have a question
that's not trivial,

232
00:14:39,840 --> 00:14:43,200
you typically break that
down into several steps

233
00:14:43,200 --> 00:14:46,720
and then go through them, and
then come to the final answer.

234
00:14:46,720 --> 00:14:50,960
So I guess the idea is problems
that are reasoning problems,

235
00:14:50,960 --> 00:14:56,080
they would have some
pattern of that.

236
00:14:56,080 --> 00:14:58,480
So to illustrate
this, let's just

237
00:14:58,480 --> 00:15:01,520
make sure we're all kind
of thinking the same.

238
00:15:01,520 --> 00:15:04,320
So a non-reasoning
question would

239
00:15:04,320 --> 00:15:08,720
be something what is the course
code of Stanford's transformers

240
00:15:08,720 --> 00:15:10,240
and LLM class.

241
00:15:10,240 --> 00:15:12,320
So this one, it's
a knowledge thing.

242
00:15:12,320 --> 00:15:15,680
Everyone knows it's CME 295.

243
00:15:15,680 --> 00:15:19,760
But then as opposed to
that, in contrast to that,

244
00:15:19,760 --> 00:15:23,360
a reasoning-based question
would be maybe a math question.

245
00:15:23,360 --> 00:15:25,120
So for instance,
let's suppose we have

246
00:15:25,120 --> 00:15:27,680
a bear that was born in 2020.

247
00:15:27,680 --> 00:15:30,320
How old is that
bear now in 2025?

248
00:15:30,320 --> 00:15:33,760
So that would be the kind of
question that we're looking at.

249
00:15:33,760 --> 00:15:35,560
Of course, this is super easy.

250
00:15:35,560 --> 00:15:38,800
You can think of something
that's much harder than that,

251
00:15:38,800 --> 00:15:42,560
and this would qualify.

252
00:15:42,560 --> 00:15:43,840
Cool.

253
00:15:44,800 --> 00:15:50,240
So now that we a little
bit what reasoning is, now

254
00:15:50,240 --> 00:15:52,880
we're going to
look at how we can,

255
00:15:52,880 --> 00:15:55,600
I guess, obtain a
model that can deal

256
00:15:55,600 --> 00:15:58,480
with these kinds of prompts.

257
00:15:59,440 --> 00:16:04,960
So the core idea here
is to leverage a concept

258
00:16:04,960 --> 00:16:08,080
we saw earlier in the class.

259
00:16:08,080 --> 00:16:10,160
So I'm not sure if
you remember, but back

260
00:16:10,160 --> 00:16:14,080
in lecture maybe
two or three, we

261
00:16:14,080 --> 00:16:18,400
saw a technique called
chain of thought.

262
00:16:18,400 --> 00:16:22,480
So who remembers what
chain of thought is?

263
00:16:22,480 --> 00:16:23,520
Yeah?

264
00:16:23,520 --> 00:16:26,640
Yes, do you want to
say what that is?

265
00:16:32,000 --> 00:16:32,640
Yeah, exactly.

266
00:16:32,640 --> 00:16:34,800
So the answer is
thinking in steps

267
00:16:35,680 --> 00:16:38,400
instead of just giving
just a blanket answer.

268
00:16:38,400 --> 00:16:39,840
So great answer.

269
00:16:39,840 --> 00:16:42,160
So here, just to illustrate--

270
00:16:42,160 --> 00:16:46,320
yeah.

271
00:16:58,000 --> 00:16:59,280
Oh, yeah.

272
00:16:59,280 --> 00:16:59,840
Great point.

273
00:16:59,840 --> 00:17:02,320
So the question is,
for some questions,

274
00:17:02,320 --> 00:17:05,200
you need to have some
element of context.

275
00:17:05,200 --> 00:17:08,160
So for instance, here,
you need for your LLM

276
00:17:08,160 --> 00:17:14,240
to know that this year, I don't
know, today is November 7, 2025.

277
00:17:14,240 --> 00:17:15,440
So yes great points.

278
00:17:16,400 --> 00:17:18,320
So there are two parts of that.

279
00:17:18,320 --> 00:17:21,360
For that specific
question, so typically

280
00:17:21,360 --> 00:17:25,280
LLMs they have something
that we call preamble.

281
00:17:25,280 --> 00:17:28,640
So something that tells
you about some context.

282
00:17:28,640 --> 00:17:30,320
And typically the
date is something

283
00:17:30,320 --> 00:17:32,240
that we put in the preamble.

284
00:17:32,240 --> 00:17:34,880
So for this very
specific case, the date

285
00:17:34,880 --> 00:17:40,000
would be information that
would already be, I guess,

286
00:17:40,000 --> 00:17:41,840
available to the LLM.

287
00:17:41,840 --> 00:17:44,560
But for some other
problems, you can very well

288
00:17:44,560 --> 00:17:48,480
have information or context
that you do not have.

289
00:17:48,480 --> 00:17:53,840
And in lecture 7, we will
see how we can fetch that.

290
00:17:53,840 --> 00:17:57,200
And it's definitely something
that will be very useful.

291
00:17:58,160 --> 00:18:02,640
But for the sake of today,
we will consider this more

292
00:18:02,640 --> 00:18:06,000
as being an extension of
reasoning models as opposed

293
00:18:06,000 --> 00:18:09,680
to something that is
foundational to how they work.

294
00:18:09,680 --> 00:18:15,520
But we'll respond to this
part, I guess, next lecture.

295
00:18:15,520 --> 00:18:16,640
Cool.

296
00:18:16,640 --> 00:18:19,600
And so here, we are
about to illustrate what

297
00:18:19,600 --> 00:18:21,680
a chain of thought looked like.

298
00:18:21,680 --> 00:18:25,120
And so here, instead of
having, as you mentioned,

299
00:18:25,120 --> 00:18:27,520
just a blanket
answer, what we want

300
00:18:27,520 --> 00:18:31,360
is to explain also
the reasoning.

301
00:18:31,360 --> 00:18:34,240
So the way chain of
thought did that was

302
00:18:34,240 --> 00:18:40,000
by having some in-context
learning examples that

303
00:18:40,000 --> 00:18:44,720
explicitly the reasoning
to encourage the model

304
00:18:44,720 --> 00:18:49,520
to also do that before
providing the answer.

305
00:18:49,520 --> 00:18:51,840
So that's the rough--

306
00:18:51,840 --> 00:18:52,800
it's not the rough idea.

307
00:18:52,800 --> 00:18:56,640
It's the idea behind
chain of thought.

308
00:18:56,640 --> 00:19:00,880
And here, what we want
to do is to do that,

309
00:19:00,880 --> 00:19:05,600
but at a much larger scale.

310
00:19:05,600 --> 00:19:08,320
So I just want to
build an intuition

311
00:19:08,320 --> 00:19:13,120
as to why this may help us.

312
00:19:13,120 --> 00:19:16,320
So LLMs, they are
basically trained

313
00:19:16,320 --> 00:19:20,240
with this next token
prediction objective.

314
00:19:20,240 --> 00:19:24,720
And so the way they respond
to questions that we ask

315
00:19:24,720 --> 00:19:31,360
is typically to sound plausible
in a way to maximize or optimize

316
00:19:31,360 --> 00:19:33,360
for the probability
of the tokens

317
00:19:33,360 --> 00:19:36,560
that you want to
generate to happen.

318
00:19:36,560 --> 00:19:40,320
So if you have a very hard
problem that you're presenting

319
00:19:40,320 --> 00:19:43,520
to the LLM, there
are very few chances

320
00:19:43,520 --> 00:19:49,600
that that problem appeared
in the training sets.

321
00:19:49,600 --> 00:19:54,720
And so here, the idea is to have
the LLM decompose the problem

322
00:19:54,720 --> 00:20:00,080
into tractable ones, and
then rely on the patterns

323
00:20:00,080 --> 00:20:04,800
that it has seen during
training to solve all these

324
00:20:04,800 --> 00:20:06,800
more tractable problems.

325
00:20:06,800 --> 00:20:11,200
And it's a little bit like
you or when we were students.

326
00:20:11,200 --> 00:20:17,040
When we give you a problem, you
try to link it back to something

327
00:20:17,040 --> 00:20:19,840
that you know, that you
have seen at training time,

328
00:20:19,840 --> 00:20:23,280
like during your
studying, to solve them

329
00:20:23,280 --> 00:20:26,400
in order to find the answer.

330
00:20:26,400 --> 00:20:29,280
So I guess that's the intuition.

331
00:20:29,280 --> 00:20:31,520
I guess another reason
that you can think of

332
00:20:31,520 --> 00:20:37,680
is when you let the LLM generate
more tokens, you're just

333
00:20:37,680 --> 00:20:40,080
giving it more
compute, if you think

334
00:20:40,080 --> 00:20:43,600
about it, because at
each generation step,

335
00:20:43,600 --> 00:20:47,360
you have this
whole forward pass.

336
00:20:47,360 --> 00:20:53,760
And when you do that more,
you just give it more compute.

337
00:20:53,760 --> 00:20:56,000
And we will see
there is a term that

338
00:20:56,000 --> 00:21:00,080
is dubbed compute budgets,
which is, I guess,

339
00:21:00,080 --> 00:21:01,840
the budget that
you want your LLM

340
00:21:01,840 --> 00:21:04,160
to have to generate
your response that we

341
00:21:04,160 --> 00:21:06,080
will see later on.

342
00:21:06,080 --> 00:21:08,560
But yeah, so that
also plays a role.

343
00:21:09,520 --> 00:21:14,080
So is everyone clear
on the overall idea

344
00:21:14,080 --> 00:21:17,040
of what a reasoning model is?

345
00:21:17,040 --> 00:21:19,520
Yeah?

346
00:21:19,520 --> 00:21:20,160
Perfect.

347
00:21:20,160 --> 00:21:23,600
So just to make sure, again,
that we're all clear on this,

348
00:21:23,600 --> 00:21:29,600
so up until now we had, quote
unquote, Vanilla LLMs that

349
00:21:29,600 --> 00:21:35,200
had some question as inputs,
and they were responding

350
00:21:35,200 --> 00:21:37,280
with something as output.

351
00:21:38,560 --> 00:21:45,920
And in our case, what we want
is given a question as input,

352
00:21:45,920 --> 00:21:49,440
we don't want to directly
generate an answer.

353
00:21:49,440 --> 00:21:53,360
We first want to think.

354
00:21:53,360 --> 00:21:57,280
And here, I guess we think by
first outputting a reasoning

355
00:21:57,280 --> 00:21:58,880
chain.

356
00:21:58,880 --> 00:22:03,440
And then we provide the answer.

357
00:22:03,440 --> 00:22:09,120
So here, the LLM output
is not just the answer.

358
00:22:09,120 --> 00:22:18,160
It's the reasoning
plus the answer.

359
00:22:18,160 --> 00:22:21,760
And I guess here, I was
saying that this topic

360
00:22:21,760 --> 00:22:24,480
has been very hot and
trendy for the past year.

361
00:22:24,480 --> 00:22:28,000
So this is a little bit of
a preview of the timeline

362
00:22:28,000 --> 00:22:29,520
of reasoning models.

363
00:22:30,480 --> 00:22:35,040
So reasoning itself is a topic
that has been studied for more

364
00:22:35,040 --> 00:22:41,920
than a year, but reasoning
models have started popping out

365
00:22:41,920 --> 00:22:45,680
starting from OpenAI's
release of 01 preview.

366
00:22:45,680 --> 00:22:50,320
And this one was
September of 2024.

367
00:22:50,320 --> 00:22:53,120
And then after
that, you basically

368
00:22:53,120 --> 00:22:56,720
have everyone just
wondering how OpenAI did it.

369
00:22:56,720 --> 00:22:59,680
And so you had all
of these AI labs

370
00:22:59,680 --> 00:23:05,520
trying to see what we
can do to, I guess,

371
00:23:05,520 --> 00:23:07,360
increase the reasoning
abilities of the model.

372
00:23:07,360 --> 00:23:09,760
So you would have
everyone working on this.

373
00:23:09,760 --> 00:23:15,040
And then you had Google's
Gemini 2.0 flash thinking

374
00:23:15,040 --> 00:23:18,640
that was, I think,
released in December.

375
00:23:18,640 --> 00:23:24,400
And then starting in 2025,
there was this DeepSeek R1 paper

376
00:23:24,400 --> 00:23:29,280
that was published in January,
which made a lot of noise

377
00:23:29,280 --> 00:23:31,360
because what they
were able to do

378
00:23:31,360 --> 00:23:36,640
was to match OpenAI's
reasoning ability

379
00:23:36,640 --> 00:23:41,600
performance with a method
that they were actually

380
00:23:42,160 --> 00:23:44,800
describing in their paper.

381
00:23:44,800 --> 00:23:48,400
So that was a big
moment, January 2025.

382
00:23:48,400 --> 00:23:52,080
And then after that, all
of these other models

383
00:23:52,080 --> 00:23:55,440
also had reasoning
abilities added.

384
00:23:55,440 --> 00:24:01,200
So you had some models from xAI,
from Anthropic with Claudes,

385
00:24:01,200 --> 00:24:07,120
and then from other labs
as well, also from Mistral.

386
00:24:07,120 --> 00:24:08,800
So this timeline
is not exhaustive,

387
00:24:08,800 --> 00:24:10,640
but it's just to
show you, I guess,

388
00:24:10,640 --> 00:24:13,520
how recent these models are.

389
00:24:13,520 --> 00:24:15,280
And I guess one
thing to have in mind

390
00:24:15,280 --> 00:24:22,240
is it basically started
at the end of 2024.

391
00:24:22,240 --> 00:24:23,040
Cool.

392
00:24:23,040 --> 00:24:26,640
So I know a lot of
you, if not all of you,

393
00:24:26,640 --> 00:24:30,880
are using LLMs every day as
chat bots like, let's say,

394
00:24:30,880 --> 00:24:33,040
ChatGPT or Gemini.

395
00:24:33,040 --> 00:24:36,960
And so I want you to
know, when the model

396
00:24:36,960 --> 00:24:40,640
that you're interacting
with is a reasoning model--

397
00:24:40,640 --> 00:24:43,680
so I have a question for you.

398
00:24:43,680 --> 00:24:46,640
I was having a discussion
with ChatGPT the other day.

399
00:24:46,640 --> 00:24:52,640
And I was wondering, is this
using a reasoning model.

400
00:24:52,640 --> 00:24:53,760
So what do you think?

401
00:24:53,760 --> 00:24:58,320
If you stare at this screenshot.

402
00:24:58,320 --> 00:24:58,800
Yeah?

403
00:24:58,800 --> 00:25:01,920
Why?

404
00:25:01,920 --> 00:25:02,880
Right, exactly.

405
00:25:02,880 --> 00:25:04,800
So the key word
here is thinking.

406
00:25:04,800 --> 00:25:06,800
Actually, they
put it everywhere.

407
00:25:06,800 --> 00:25:13,760
But when these UIs show
you the thinking process,

408
00:25:13,760 --> 00:25:16,720
so what they do is actually--

409
00:25:16,720 --> 00:25:19,360
so they don't show you actually
the full reasoning process.

410
00:25:19,360 --> 00:25:21,920
And we're going to see why.

411
00:25:21,920 --> 00:25:26,400
But they tell you that
they spend time thinking.

412
00:25:26,400 --> 00:25:29,360
And that time
thinking is actually

413
00:25:29,360 --> 00:25:32,880
the time that is needed to
produce the reasoning chain.

414
00:25:32,880 --> 00:25:36,800
That can be, I guess, more or
less something that takes time.

415
00:25:36,800 --> 00:25:38,480
And so for instance,
for ChatGPT,

416
00:25:38,480 --> 00:25:42,960
you have this thinking that you
can also change from standard

417
00:25:42,960 --> 00:25:44,800
to extended, et cetera.

418
00:25:44,800 --> 00:25:48,800
And you have this for
other models as well.

419
00:25:48,800 --> 00:25:53,120
And in particular,
the, quote unquote,

420
00:25:53,120 --> 00:25:59,520
thought summary that you see
is not the raw reasoning chain.

421
00:25:59,520 --> 00:26:02,160
It's a summary of it.

422
00:26:02,160 --> 00:26:04,000
And the reason
why they do that--

423
00:26:04,000 --> 00:26:07,440
I mean, I'm
hypothesizing-- is one,

424
00:26:07,440 --> 00:26:10,320
because the raw chain
may not be something

425
00:26:10,320 --> 00:26:14,320
that is fully intelligible
from a human standpoint.

426
00:26:15,040 --> 00:26:17,040
Second is because
maybe you as a user,

427
00:26:17,040 --> 00:26:21,040
you don't want to read
the pages and pages.

428
00:26:21,040 --> 00:26:23,440
And then third, this is
going to be what we see.

429
00:26:23,440 --> 00:26:27,040
But if you have the
reasoning chains,

430
00:26:29,120 --> 00:26:35,920
you can maybe train a model
that is trained on these chains

431
00:26:35,920 --> 00:26:40,000
so it can basically mimic
those abilities as well.

432
00:26:40,000 --> 00:26:43,920
So this may be the reasons
why you would typically not

433
00:26:43,920 --> 00:26:47,520
see the raw chain.

434
00:26:47,520 --> 00:26:50,560
And when it comes
to pricing, so we

435
00:26:50,560 --> 00:26:53,280
saw that the output
of reasoning models

436
00:26:53,280 --> 00:26:57,760
are not only the answer, but
also the reasoning itself.

437
00:26:57,760 --> 00:27:00,880
And so you will see in, I
guess, all of these APIs

438
00:27:00,880 --> 00:27:03,760
that you're actually
getting charged for it.

439
00:27:03,760 --> 00:27:07,680
So you're not necessarily
getting all the reasoning chain.

440
00:27:07,680 --> 00:27:11,760
But if you look at the
docs, there's always,

441
00:27:11,760 --> 00:27:14,080
I guess, a sentence
or two, I guess,

442
00:27:14,080 --> 00:27:16,880
that specifies that
you're actually being

443
00:27:16,880 --> 00:27:18,640
charged for output tokens.

444
00:27:18,640 --> 00:27:23,680
And those output tokens, they
also include reasoning tokens.

445
00:27:23,680 --> 00:27:27,200
So I think that's also
a good thing to know.

446
00:27:28,320 --> 00:27:33,040
And I guess from
a user standpoint,

447
00:27:33,040 --> 00:27:39,600
this also gives an incentive
to have the maximum reasoning

448
00:27:39,600 --> 00:27:43,920
ability for a minimum
amount of reasoning token

449
00:27:43,920 --> 00:27:47,120
because you don't
want to pay a lot.

450
00:27:48,160 --> 00:27:51,040
So we're going to see later
on how we can deal with that.

451
00:27:51,040 --> 00:27:55,360
But this is just one
thing that's good to note.

452
00:27:55,360 --> 00:27:56,400
Cool.

453
00:27:56,400 --> 00:27:59,600
So we talked about what
reasoning was, or at least

454
00:27:59,600 --> 00:28:01,840
a tentative definition.

455
00:28:01,840 --> 00:28:05,680
We saw, I guess, the core
idea behind reasoning models.

456
00:28:05,680 --> 00:28:09,120
So now we're going to talk
about some of the benchmarks

457
00:28:09,120 --> 00:28:13,680
that people use to quantify
reasoning abilities.

458
00:28:13,680 --> 00:28:16,160
So the first one, as I
previously mentioned,

459
00:28:16,160 --> 00:28:20,400
is about assessing
the coding abilities.

460
00:28:20,400 --> 00:28:23,360
And so here, the
goal is typically

461
00:28:23,360 --> 00:28:27,440
to solve a coding
problem or to fix a bug.

462
00:28:27,440 --> 00:28:30,800
So you typically have
the following setup.

463
00:28:30,800 --> 00:28:38,880
So given a problem, you want
to produce a solution that

464
00:28:38,880 --> 00:28:43,120
is able to pass test cases.

465
00:28:43,120 --> 00:28:47,600
So if you have a solution
that passes all test cases,

466
00:28:47,600 --> 00:28:50,880
then you have a
solution that works.

467
00:28:50,880 --> 00:28:57,600
And this is our way of
verifying that a response that

468
00:28:57,600 --> 00:29:00,080
was generated is
actually a correct one.

469
00:29:01,680 --> 00:29:04,480
So that's for coding.

470
00:29:05,360 --> 00:29:07,920
So just giving you an overview
of the kinds of benchmarks

471
00:29:07,920 --> 00:29:08,720
that are out there.

472
00:29:08,720 --> 00:29:14,320
So we have HumanEval, which is
the screenshot screenshots here,

473
00:29:14,320 --> 00:29:18,560
which I believe is a set of 100
something coding problems that

474
00:29:18,560 --> 00:29:23,200
were human written, which is
why it's called the HumanEval.

475
00:29:23,200 --> 00:29:26,160
But you have then
CodeForces, which

476
00:29:26,160 --> 00:29:29,200
is coming from a website
of competitive programming

477
00:29:29,200 --> 00:29:31,120
that some of you may know.

478
00:29:31,120 --> 00:29:34,560
And there is also SWE-bench,
which is, I believe,

479
00:29:34,560 --> 00:29:38,640
a set of problems that were
derived from GitHub issues.

480
00:29:38,640 --> 00:29:41,040
So these are real
practical problems.

481
00:29:41,040 --> 00:29:46,720
So you will see that these
reasoning models in the reports,

482
00:29:46,720 --> 00:29:51,920
they typically have results
along these benchmarks.

483
00:29:52,640 --> 00:29:55,040
So this is for coding.

484
00:29:55,040 --> 00:30:00,000
Now for math, the goal
is to solve a problem.

485
00:30:00,000 --> 00:30:04,480
And the way it works
here is given a problem,

486
00:30:04,480 --> 00:30:06,160
you want the answer.

487
00:30:06,160 --> 00:30:08,400
And of course, you're
letting your model,

488
00:30:09,280 --> 00:30:12,560
generate some reasoning.

489
00:30:12,560 --> 00:30:16,480
And so here, what you would do
to verify that your solution

490
00:30:16,480 --> 00:30:25,040
works is by parsing the answer
like so and then comparing it

491
00:30:25,040 --> 00:30:27,920
with some ground truth.

492
00:30:27,920 --> 00:30:32,000
So here, we can really
know if the answer

493
00:30:32,000 --> 00:30:37,600
that your model is producing
is true by comparing the two.

494
00:30:37,600 --> 00:30:40,160
So you will ask me OK,
