743
00:47:38,080 --> 00:47:40,640
There's another one
that you may see,

744
00:47:40,640 --> 00:47:45,120
which is called
consensus at k, which

745
00:47:45,120 --> 00:47:52,160
is the answer that is coming
from the highest number of times

746
00:47:52,160 --> 00:47:56,400
that the answer appears
among your generations.

747
00:47:56,400 --> 00:47:58,880
And you can think of the
self-consistency technique

748
00:47:58,880 --> 00:48:01,760
as being very related to that.

749
00:48:02,480 --> 00:48:03,280
So you may see that.

750
00:48:03,280 --> 00:48:06,080
And then the other metrics that
you will see in those benchmarks

751
00:48:06,080 --> 00:48:07,440
are typically the
ones that you're

752
00:48:07,440 --> 00:48:14,640
familiar with like accuracy,
exact match, and so on.

753
00:48:15,760 --> 00:48:17,760
I took a lot of time
on this first part.

754
00:48:17,760 --> 00:48:19,920
I think I need to
go a bit faster.

755
00:48:19,920 --> 00:48:24,240
But does that roughly
make sense so far?

756
00:48:24,240 --> 00:48:25,440
Yeah?

757
00:48:25,440 --> 00:48:30,480
So right now, I hope you
what a reasoning model is.

758
00:48:30,480 --> 00:48:33,760
So now we're going to go into
the most interesting part

759
00:48:33,760 --> 00:48:39,040
of the lecture, which is how can
we build such a reasoning model.

760
00:48:39,040 --> 00:48:41,920
So we know we want
our reasoning model

761
00:48:41,920 --> 00:48:44,160
to produce a reasoning chain.

762
00:48:44,160 --> 00:48:48,400
But right now, we don't really
how to do that at scale.

763
00:48:48,400 --> 00:48:52,800
And this is going to be the
main focus in this part.

764
00:48:52,800 --> 00:48:59,280
So here the idea is to
somehow incentivize the model

765
00:48:59,280 --> 00:49:03,600
to produce a chain of
thought or reasoning chain

766
00:49:03,600 --> 00:49:05,680
before answering.

767
00:49:06,640 --> 00:49:14,080
So the problem with that is
that reasoning chains writing

768
00:49:14,080 --> 00:49:18,480
is a very tough task,
especially for, I guess,

769
00:49:20,400 --> 00:49:22,720
long reasoning chains.

770
00:49:22,720 --> 00:49:25,280
And for that,
let's suppose if we

771
00:49:25,280 --> 00:49:28,080
were to go look into our
toolbox of the techniques

772
00:49:28,080 --> 00:49:30,400
we have learned so far,
maybe we can think,

773
00:49:30,400 --> 00:49:33,920
OK, we can use SFT to do that.

774
00:49:33,920 --> 00:49:37,200
But the problem with SFT is
you need high quality data,

775
00:49:37,200 --> 00:49:39,120
and in particular,
you would need

776
00:49:39,120 --> 00:49:43,120
to write all of these
reasoning chains.

777
00:49:43,120 --> 00:49:45,120
Let's suppose you do not
have this reasoning chains.

778
00:49:45,120 --> 00:49:46,560
So how do you do that?

779
00:49:46,560 --> 00:49:48,880
You would typically
write them from scratch.

780
00:49:48,880 --> 00:49:52,000
But that is very hard.

781
00:49:52,000 --> 00:49:56,640
So that's one, I guess,
one vote to not do SFT,

782
00:49:56,640 --> 00:49:59,200
if we don't have any
reasoning chains.

783
00:50:00,080 --> 00:50:04,720
So the second reason here
is, or the second fact,

784
00:50:04,720 --> 00:50:08,080
is that the way
the model reasons

785
00:50:08,080 --> 00:50:12,640
may be different from
the way we reason.

786
00:50:12,640 --> 00:50:18,880
And for that, maybe a
human written reasoning

787
00:50:18,880 --> 00:50:25,360
may not be the best way to teach
the model on how to reason.

788
00:50:25,360 --> 00:50:27,520
So that's the second
fact, which is

789
00:50:27,520 --> 00:50:31,440
going against having some
human written reasoning

790
00:50:31,440 --> 00:50:34,400
chains as SFT data.

791
00:50:34,400 --> 00:50:36,480
And then the third
fact that I want to say

792
00:50:36,480 --> 00:50:40,800
is we just saw that
these reasoning tasks,

793
00:50:40,800 --> 00:50:47,280
they have a very natural reward,
which is actually verifiable.

794
00:50:47,280 --> 00:50:50,400
So for coding, you know
if your thing works,

795
00:50:50,400 --> 00:50:54,320
if it passes some test
cases, if it compiles,

796
00:50:54,320 --> 00:50:57,520
and for math, you know if
it works if the answer is

797
00:50:57,520 --> 00:51:01,280
the same as your ground truth.

798
00:51:01,280 --> 00:51:05,920
So naturally, you do
have a reward signal.

799
00:51:05,920 --> 00:51:08,960
So we saw there's
a reward signal.

800
00:51:08,960 --> 00:51:13,760
SFT is not a great way
to start from scratch.

801
00:51:13,760 --> 00:51:15,680
Well, what do you do?

802
00:51:15,680 --> 00:51:18,720
Well, let's try RL then.

803
00:51:18,720 --> 00:51:21,600
And the good thing
is last week, we

804
00:51:21,600 --> 00:51:26,320
saw how RL works in
the case of LLMs.

805
00:51:26,320 --> 00:51:30,080
So I guess that's
a great timing.

806
00:51:30,080 --> 00:51:31,680
So how would we do that?

807
00:51:32,240 --> 00:51:38,000
So just as a reminder, we
want to teach our model

808
00:51:38,000 --> 00:51:42,240
to solve these more
complicated problems.

809
00:51:42,240 --> 00:51:48,000
And we also want to teach
it to reason before.

810
00:51:48,000 --> 00:51:50,720
So in order to do
that, we first want

811
00:51:50,720 --> 00:51:56,400
to have a reward that checks
whether the reasoning chain is

812
00:51:56,400 --> 00:51:57,440
there.

813
00:51:58,160 --> 00:52:00,240
So here, you can
do that by simply

814
00:52:00,240 --> 00:52:04,720
checking whether the model has
produced a reasoning chain.

815
00:52:04,720 --> 00:52:07,760
And you can check that
by checking the presence,

816
00:52:07,760 --> 00:52:12,400
let's say, of the think,
start, and end token

817
00:52:12,400 --> 00:52:14,320
that you can instruct
your model to use

818
00:52:14,320 --> 00:52:18,400
to insert its reasoning chain.

819
00:52:18,400 --> 00:52:20,080
And then the second
reward that you

820
00:52:20,080 --> 00:52:26,080
want to have is to check that
the solution that it produced

821
00:52:26,080 --> 00:52:27,840
actually works.

822
00:52:27,840 --> 00:52:29,600
And so here, as
we mentioned, this

823
00:52:29,600 --> 00:52:31,840
is something that you can
actually do for the benchmarks

824
00:52:31,840 --> 00:52:33,280
that we care about.

825
00:52:33,280 --> 00:52:37,360
So for codes, you would check
that it works for all cases.

826
00:52:37,360 --> 00:52:39,760
For math, you would
just verify with respect

827
00:52:39,760 --> 00:52:43,680
to the answer being the
same as the ground truth.

828
00:52:43,680 --> 00:52:47,920
So we also have that.

829
00:52:47,920 --> 00:52:53,360
So in summary, we
will run RL, and we

830
00:52:53,360 --> 00:53:00,240
will run RL using a reward that
is a combination of checking

831
00:53:00,240 --> 00:53:04,640
whether the thing
tokens are here

832
00:53:04,640 --> 00:53:08,400
and that the end
result is correct.

833
00:53:08,400 --> 00:53:11,440
And we saw that both of
them, we can do this easily.

834
00:53:11,440 --> 00:53:15,840
No need for a model.

835
00:53:16,560 --> 00:53:17,920
So let's suppose you do that.

836
00:53:17,920 --> 00:53:22,240
Let's suppose you do
RL on search rewards.

837
00:53:22,240 --> 00:53:24,720
Well, the nice
thing that you see

838
00:53:24,720 --> 00:53:30,000
is if you plot the performance
of the model with respect

839
00:53:30,000 --> 00:53:32,960
to one of those benchmarks that
I mentioned-- so here it's aim.

840
00:53:32,960 --> 00:53:35,920
So if you remember, it's
the math benchmark--

841
00:53:35,920 --> 00:53:41,600
you see that as you
perform your RL steps,

842
00:53:41,600 --> 00:53:44,800
the performance of the
model on those benchmarks,

843
00:53:44,800 --> 00:53:46,160
they actually increase.

844
00:53:46,160 --> 00:53:49,680
And they actually increase
quite significantly.

845
00:53:49,680 --> 00:53:53,200
So the graph here is actually
coming from the training

846
00:53:53,200 --> 00:53:54,880
of DeepSeek R1--

847
00:53:54,880 --> 00:53:58,160
actually, R1-Zero here, which
we will see a little bit more

848
00:53:58,160 --> 00:54:01,280
in detail with Shervine
how it actually works.

849
00:54:01,280 --> 00:54:06,720
But you can see that if you
incentivize the model to think

850
00:54:06,720 --> 00:54:10,320
and produce the right
answer, it can actually

851
00:54:10,320 --> 00:54:14,640
learn quite meaningfully,
only with these two

852
00:54:14,640 --> 00:54:19,200
verifiable rewards.

853
00:54:19,840 --> 00:54:23,200
But now you may
wonder, let's suppose

854
00:54:23,200 --> 00:54:29,280
I'm teaching my model to think,
well, not all prompts are equal.

855
00:54:29,280 --> 00:54:31,200
There are some
prompts that do not

856
00:54:31,200 --> 00:54:35,040
need the model to think
too much as opposed

857
00:54:35,040 --> 00:54:40,320
to other prompts which would
need a little bit of thinking.

858
00:54:40,320 --> 00:54:43,040
So there has been
a lot of, I guess,

859
00:54:43,040 --> 00:54:47,040
work happening in
the community as how

860
00:54:47,040 --> 00:54:50,480
to control the amount of
thinking that the model does.

861
00:54:51,200 --> 00:54:55,440
So you have things
like dynamic budget

862
00:54:55,440 --> 00:54:58,400
that you will see out
there, how can we make sure

863
00:54:58,400 --> 00:55:03,840
that the model does not
overthink on questions that

864
00:55:03,840 --> 00:55:06,240
do not need too much thinking.

865
00:55:06,240 --> 00:55:07,920
So for this, you
can have something

866
00:55:07,920 --> 00:55:12,080
like a quick classifier, let's
say, that runs on the prompt

867
00:55:12,080 --> 00:55:14,000
and tells you whether
it's something that

868
00:55:14,000 --> 00:55:17,680
is kind of a high thinking kind
of problem or a low thinking

869
00:55:17,680 --> 00:55:19,200
one.

870
00:55:19,200 --> 00:55:20,800
But this is more
of an open problem.

871
00:55:20,800 --> 00:55:24,080
But this can be one solution.

872
00:55:24,080 --> 00:55:28,800
So the second one
is those LLMs, they

873
00:55:28,800 --> 00:55:32,480
have a limited context window.

874
00:55:32,480 --> 00:55:35,920
So when the LLM
thinks, it needs to.

875
00:55:35,920 --> 00:55:42,880
Also be aware of how much
context length is left.

876
00:55:42,880 --> 00:55:47,920
It cannot think too much also
because of that limitation.

877
00:55:47,920 --> 00:55:52,080
So you need to also have
that context awareness.

878
00:55:52,080 --> 00:55:55,920
So there has been some work
to also force the model

879
00:55:55,920 --> 00:56:00,080
to either think more or stop.

880
00:56:00,080 --> 00:56:02,880
So there is this
term, budget forcing,

881
00:56:02,880 --> 00:56:06,160
that I think was introduced
in this paper, S1.

882
00:56:06,160 --> 00:56:13,120
So the idea here is if you want
your model to continue thinking,

883
00:56:13,120 --> 00:56:16,880
you're going to introduce
some tokens mid-way to force

884
00:56:16,880 --> 00:56:18,800
it to think more.

885
00:56:18,800 --> 00:56:23,200
And such tokens are,
for instance, weights.

886
00:56:23,200 --> 00:56:25,600
I think there is
another solution.

887
00:56:25,600 --> 00:56:28,560
So actually, it's a slide that
I have not really talked about.

888
00:56:29,760 --> 00:56:31,600
So if you look at
this reasoning chain,

889
00:56:31,600 --> 00:56:33,360
sometimes the model will
output something like,

890
00:56:33,360 --> 00:56:36,320
oh wait, wait, wait, I think
I found something else.

891
00:56:36,320 --> 00:56:38,800
And typically, the
model would go again

892
00:56:38,800 --> 00:56:42,240
on another kind
of reasoning path.

893
00:56:42,240 --> 00:56:46,400
And this can be one way
to incentivize your model

894
00:56:46,400 --> 00:56:49,200
to think more.

895
00:56:49,200 --> 00:56:52,800
Or another term can be,
OK, your time is up.

896
00:56:52,800 --> 00:56:58,720
Now my answer is, and it will
force your model to respond.

897
00:56:58,720 --> 00:57:04,800
And then if you think
about it, your model

898
00:57:04,800 --> 00:57:08,080
gives tokens in its
reasoning chain,

899
00:57:08,080 --> 00:57:13,920
but models may think on
some other space, maybe

900
00:57:13,920 --> 00:57:16,080
not in the language space.

901
00:57:16,080 --> 00:57:19,360
So there is also a line
of work around having

902
00:57:19,360 --> 00:57:22,160
some continuous thoughts.

903
00:57:22,160 --> 00:57:25,680
Basically having this thinking
token actually not be tokens,

904
00:57:25,680 --> 00:57:28,320
but be hidden
representations that

905
00:57:28,320 --> 00:57:32,320
can be more meaningful,
but also more compressed.

906
00:57:32,320 --> 00:57:34,400
So you have a bunch
of papers on this.

907
00:57:34,400 --> 00:57:38,640
So there's one that we linked,
which is actually from 2024.

908
00:57:38,640 --> 00:57:40,640
But I think even a
few days ago, I also

909
00:57:40,640 --> 00:57:42,560
saw another paper on that.

910
00:57:42,560 --> 00:57:49,520
So it's very much
active area of research.

911
00:57:49,520 --> 00:57:53,440
And I guess just
like that, I guess

912
00:57:53,440 --> 00:58:01,760
we saw that the way that we want
to scale our model is with RL.

913
00:58:01,760 --> 00:58:03,680
I guess is everyone
convinced of that?

914
00:58:03,680 --> 00:58:06,080
Did I convince you well
with those arguments,

915
00:58:06,080 --> 00:58:09,600
or does anyone have
any questions on this?

916
00:58:09,600 --> 00:58:12,640
And I guess here,
I want you to have

917
00:58:12,640 --> 00:58:19,600
a takeaway, which is we want to
use RL to incentivize our model

918
00:58:19,600 --> 00:58:23,680
to think more if we
start from scratch,

919
00:58:23,680 --> 00:58:27,040
meaning we don't have
reasoning chains.

920
00:58:27,040 --> 00:58:31,120
So is everyone good with this?

921
00:58:31,120 --> 00:58:34,320
Yeah?

922
00:58:34,320 --> 00:58:35,360
Kind of, yeah.

923
00:58:35,360 --> 00:58:37,840
So I'll take this as a yes.

924
00:58:37,840 --> 00:58:41,040
So now we're going to
see the algorithm that we

925
00:58:41,040 --> 00:58:45,360
use to perform that RL step.

926
00:58:45,360 --> 00:58:49,760
And you may have heard
this acronym a lot.

927
00:58:49,760 --> 00:58:54,480
So this algorithm that we
will see is called GRPO.

928
00:58:54,480 --> 00:58:58,480
And GRPO has been
released in 2024.

929
00:58:58,480 --> 00:59:03,200
And it has been the go
to RL algorithm for all

930
00:59:03,200 --> 00:59:09,040
these reasoning tasks, or for
this reasoning training tasks.

931
00:59:09,040 --> 00:59:11,520
So what is GRPO?

932
00:59:11,520 --> 00:59:18,320
So GRPO stands for group
relative policy optimization.

933
00:59:18,320 --> 00:59:25,200
And it is an RL algorithm
which, very much like PPO,

934
00:59:25,200 --> 00:59:29,040
aims to do these two
things we talked about.

935
00:59:29,040 --> 00:59:35,200
So the first one is to
maximize advantages.

936
00:59:35,200 --> 00:59:39,280
And if you remember, advantage
is something that tells you

937
00:59:39,280 --> 00:59:43,840
whether what you're producing
as an answer is better

938
00:59:43,840 --> 00:59:47,200
than what you would expect.

939
00:59:47,200 --> 00:59:49,760
So this is the first part.

940
00:59:49,760 --> 00:59:52,240
And then the second
part is that you do not

941
00:59:52,240 --> 00:59:59,840
want to deviate too much from
either the old model, which

942
00:59:59,840 --> 01:00:04,080
is the model at the
previous iteration,

943
01:00:04,080 --> 01:00:10,400
or the base model, which
is the model at SFT stage.

944
01:00:10,400 --> 01:00:16,320
So GRPO is also doing the same
thing as PPO in that sense.

945
01:00:16,320 --> 01:00:19,280
But then there is
a key difference.

946
01:00:19,280 --> 01:00:24,160
And that difference lies in
how it computes the advantage.

947
01:00:24,160 --> 01:00:30,400
So if you remember, PPO
estimated the advantage

948
01:00:30,400 --> 01:00:34,640
by taking the rewards, which
is at the completion level.

949
01:00:34,640 --> 01:00:36,960
So you know you
have your prompts,

950
01:00:36,960 --> 01:00:40,400
and you have a response,
a full response.

951
01:00:40,400 --> 01:00:44,800
And then based on those two
elements, you have a reward.

952
01:00:45,440 --> 01:00:50,080
So what PPO did was take
that into consideration

953
01:00:50,080 --> 01:00:54,880
along with something else
that it was training jointly

954
01:00:54,880 --> 01:00:59,360
at training time, which was
called the value function.

955
01:00:59,360 --> 01:01:02,800
And the value
function objective was

956
01:01:02,800 --> 01:01:07,120
to try to predict
what that reward was

957
01:01:07,120 --> 01:01:11,840
if we were to continue
generating the tokens following

958
01:01:11,840 --> 01:01:14,160
the policy.

959
01:01:14,160 --> 01:01:17,360
And if you remember, the
advantage here is actually,

960
01:01:17,360 --> 01:01:20,000
in the case of
PPO, was something

961
01:01:20,000 --> 01:01:23,920
that we obtained based
on a very complex formula

962
01:01:23,920 --> 01:01:25,200
that we did not see, actually.

963
01:01:25,200 --> 01:01:29,280
But that's called a generalized
advantage estimation.

964
01:01:29,280 --> 01:01:35,360
That is a method to
estimate those advantage.

965
01:01:35,360 --> 01:01:37,520
And the big limitation
with that was

966
01:01:37,520 --> 01:01:41,280
that you had to train a
value function jointly

967
01:01:41,280 --> 01:01:43,040
with your policy.

968
01:01:43,040 --> 01:01:45,760
So this big bottleneck.

969
01:01:45,760 --> 01:01:51,200
And in contrast to that,
GRPO says, well, we're

970
01:01:51,200 --> 01:01:53,360
not going to do that.

971
01:01:53,360 --> 01:01:56,320
We're going to
take a completion.

972
01:01:56,320 --> 01:01:59,520
We're going to
compute each reward.

973
01:01:59,520 --> 01:02:04,640
And we're going to compare it
with the average of rewards

974
01:02:04,640 --> 01:02:09,280
of completions for
that same prompt.

975
01:02:09,280 --> 01:02:11,040
So I'll give you an example.

976
01:02:11,040 --> 01:02:15,040
So let's suppose we
have a math problem.

977
01:02:15,040 --> 01:02:18,560
So what we're
saying here is we're

978
01:02:18,560 --> 01:02:21,600
going to generate
multiple completions

979
01:02:21,600 --> 01:02:25,120
for that same prompt.

980
01:02:25,120 --> 01:02:28,960
And for each prompt
and completion--

981
01:02:28,960 --> 01:02:30,800
and the prompt is shared.

982
01:02:30,800 --> 01:02:35,920
So for each completion, we're
going to measure, I guess,

983
01:02:35,920 --> 01:02:42,240
a relative measure of the
reward for that completion

984
01:02:42,240 --> 01:02:47,440
and all the other rewards
of the other completions.

985
01:02:47,440 --> 01:02:50,480
So this will give us
an idea of how much

986
01:02:50,480 --> 01:02:54,560
better or how much worse
is it from, I guess,

987
01:02:54,560 --> 01:02:56,640
the rest of the group.

988
01:02:56,640 --> 01:02:59,840
And so this is going
to be our advantage.

989
01:03:02,320 --> 01:03:08,320
So the big benefit here is that
we do not use value functions.

990
01:03:08,320 --> 01:03:09,360
We do not use that.

991
01:03:09,360 --> 01:03:14,800
The only thing we do is
we sample not just one,

992
01:03:14,800 --> 01:03:17,600
but multiple
completions in order

993
01:03:17,600 --> 01:03:25,840
to compute the average of
the rewards of the group.

994
01:03:25,840 --> 01:03:28,080
Does this make sense?

995
01:03:29,920 --> 01:03:38,720
Oh, yeah.

996
01:03:38,720 --> 01:03:46,160
So what would you do instead?

997
01:03:46,160 --> 01:03:48,800
So the question is,
why would you do that.

998
01:03:48,800 --> 01:03:53,120
Well, the traditional RL
algorithms, just for reference,

999
01:03:53,120 --> 01:03:58,240
they have been developed before
all these LLMs became a thing.

1000
01:03:58,240 --> 01:04:00,480
So for instance,
PPO was a method

1001
01:04:00,480 --> 01:04:03,280
that I believe is from 2017.

1002
01:04:03,280 --> 01:04:05,600
So these quantities,
they may make

1003
01:04:05,600 --> 01:04:08,800
a lot of sense in some
setups, but maybe not

1004
01:04:08,800 --> 01:04:10,480
in the language world.

1005
01:04:10,480 --> 01:04:14,960
And I guess here,
the idea is let's try

1006
01:04:14,960 --> 01:04:21,120
to think of something that tells
you how good your completion is

1007
01:04:21,120 --> 01:04:23,360
just in the relative sense.

1008
01:04:23,360 --> 01:04:24,960
But here, I guess
what the authors

1009
01:04:24,960 --> 01:04:28,400
want to do is to not
have to have this very

1010
01:04:28,400 --> 01:04:32,160
expensive joint model
that they have to train

1011
01:04:32,160 --> 01:04:36,000
and think of another
relative way of doing that.

1012
01:04:36,000 --> 01:04:38,800
So I think that's the
high level intuition.

1013
01:04:38,800 --> 01:04:45,440
And I guess here, the idea is
let's just sample multiple times

1014
01:04:45,440 --> 01:04:51,040
and see how one response
is comparing to the others,

1015
01:04:51,040 --> 01:04:53,920
and then use that as
some kind of baseline

1016
01:04:53,920 --> 01:04:57,600
to put this reward into context.

1017
01:04:57,600 --> 01:05:01,600
So for instance, you
may have a math problem

1018
01:05:01,600 --> 01:05:03,520
that's kind of easy.

1019
01:05:03,520 --> 01:05:07,520
And if you have a high
reward for that one,

1020
01:05:07,520 --> 01:05:11,120
maybe it's because the problem
was easy to start with.

1021
01:05:11,120 --> 01:05:15,440
But if you have, let's
say, very hard problem,

1022
01:05:15,440 --> 01:05:17,760
if you have the
correct answer, then

1023
01:05:17,760 --> 01:05:21,760
you want to make sure you're
incentivizing your model

1024
01:05:21,760 --> 01:05:26,400
to upweight those tokens
much more because if you

1025
01:05:26,400 --> 01:05:30,240
find a good solution, it's a
good solution to a hard problem.

1026
01:05:30,240 --> 01:05:34,320
So you want to somehow bake
that in into your advantage.

1027
01:05:34,320 --> 01:05:36,400
So that's the intuition.

1028
01:05:37,120 --> 01:05:40,000
So GRPO was
developed a year ago.

1029
01:05:40,000 --> 01:05:43,040
And a year ago, LLMs
were everywhere.

1030
01:05:43,040 --> 01:05:47,120
So this is also taking into
consideration, I guess,

1031
01:05:47,120 --> 01:05:52,720
what LLMs are incentivized
to do in some sense.

1032
01:05:52,720 --> 01:05:55,520
So yeah, I would
think it that way.

1033
01:05:55,520 --> 01:05:56,960
Does that help?

1034
01:05:56,960 --> 01:05:59,120
Cool, cool.

1035
01:05:59,120 --> 01:06:02,560
Any other question on this?

1036
01:06:02,560 --> 01:06:04,080
Well, don't worry if
you have questions

1037
01:06:04,080 --> 01:06:08,080
because we will have a
walkthrough of exactly how it

1038
01:06:08,080 --> 01:06:09,440
works.

1039
01:06:09,440 --> 01:06:12,800
So here, we're going to go
through the exact same thing,

1040
01:06:12,800 --> 01:06:15,520
but illustrate it.

1041
01:06:15,520 --> 01:06:22,400
So in the GRPO case,
we're taking a query,

1042
01:06:22,400 --> 01:06:24,640
and we're passing that
through our policy

1043
01:06:24,640 --> 01:06:29,040
model, which is our LLM
that we're trying to train.

1044
01:06:29,040 --> 01:06:31,760
And here, what we
said was we want

1045
01:06:31,760 --> 01:06:37,520
to generate not one, but
multiple completions.

1046
01:06:37,520 --> 01:06:41,440
Let's suppose g completions.

1047
01:06:41,440 --> 01:06:45,920
And each of these
query completions--

1048
01:06:45,920 --> 01:06:49,360
So you have g such pairs.

1049
01:06:49,360 --> 01:06:56,320
You pass them through the reward
model that gives you g rewards.

1050
01:06:56,320 --> 01:06:59,840
And what you want is to
compute the advantage which

1051
01:06:59,840 --> 01:07:02,400
puts all these rewards
into their context.

1052
01:07:02,400 --> 01:07:07,840
So we saw it was basically
the reward minus the average.

1053
01:07:07,840 --> 01:07:09,360
But it's actually
not exactly that.

1054
01:07:09,360 --> 01:07:12,720
So it's reward minus the average
over the standard deviation

1055
01:07:12,720 --> 01:07:16,320
of those rewards is
how they defined it.

1056
01:07:16,320 --> 01:07:18,160
By the way, we will
see that it may not

1057
01:07:18,160 --> 01:07:22,480
be the best way to do it, but
we'll see that in a second.

1058
01:07:22,480 --> 01:07:30,880
And we use those advantages
to then tune our policy model.

1059
01:07:30,880 --> 01:07:34,320
And while we do
that, we, of course,

1060
01:07:34,320 --> 01:07:37,520
don't want to deviate too much
for from the reference model.

1061
01:07:37,520 --> 01:07:42,400
So we have this KL divergence
term as well over here.

1062
01:07:42,400 --> 01:07:45,200
So that is GRPO.

1063
01:07:45,200 --> 01:07:48,480
And we're going to see
right now exactly how this

1064
01:07:48,480 --> 01:07:50,960
worked with PPO.

1065
01:07:50,960 --> 01:07:55,840
So with PPO, if you remember,
you have your prompt.

1066
01:07:55,840 --> 01:07:57,840
You have your query.

1067
01:07:57,840 --> 01:08:00,560
You pass that through
your policy model.

1068
01:08:00,560 --> 01:08:06,080
And you only have
one completion.

1069
01:08:06,080 --> 01:08:09,360
And you pass your prompt
and your completion.

1070
01:08:09,360 --> 01:08:13,360
So this pair, you pass it
through the reward model,

1071
01:08:13,360 --> 01:08:17,840
and this gives you a reward
for that whole completion.

1072
01:08:18,800 --> 01:08:20,640
Now, there's one
thing we did not

1073
01:08:20,640 --> 01:08:25,760
see last time, which is more
of a implementation detail.

1074
01:08:25,760 --> 01:08:30,960
But we also have a KL
divergence term that is,

1075
01:08:30,960 --> 01:08:33,840
comparing the
probability of each token

1076
01:08:33,840 --> 01:08:36,480
with the probability
of the token

1077
01:08:36,480 --> 01:08:39,280
for from the reference model.

1078
01:08:39,280 --> 01:08:42,560
And from an
implementation standpoint,

1079
01:08:42,560 --> 01:08:47,680
we also typically incorporate
that in the rewards.

1080
01:08:47,680 --> 01:08:51,760
So we have something
like a per token rewards

1081
01:08:51,760 --> 01:08:55,440
where only the last
token has the reward

1082
01:08:55,440 --> 01:08:57,360
of the whole completion.

1083
01:08:57,360 --> 01:09:01,360
But then everyone has
also a KL divergence term.

1084
01:09:01,360 --> 01:09:05,680
So that one is not super
important here to have in mind.

1085
01:09:05,680 --> 01:09:10,560
But it's just good to know that
people implement it that way.

1086
01:09:10,560 --> 01:09:14,800
So once you have those
rewards, you also

1087
01:09:14,800 --> 01:09:21,040
have a value function that
this one is per token.

1088
01:09:21,040 --> 01:09:25,520
This one tries to
quantify the rewards

1089
01:09:25,520 --> 01:09:29,600
if you were to
continue generating

1090
01:09:29,600 --> 01:09:34,400
the rest of the sequence
following the policy.

1091
01:09:34,400 --> 01:09:38,320
And we saw there is this method
that we're not going to see.

1092
01:09:38,320 --> 01:09:41,680
That is called generalized
advantage estimation

1093
01:09:41,680 --> 01:09:43,840
that takes in those
two quantities

1094
01:09:43,840 --> 01:09:45,760
and computes the advantage.

1095
01:09:45,760 --> 01:09:49,680
You can think of it as
some complicated formula.

1096
01:09:49,680 --> 01:09:57,120
And you have your advantage
that you use to tune the policy.

1097
01:09:57,120 --> 01:10:00,160
And that's it, which is
a complicated compared

1098
01:10:00,160 --> 01:10:01,600
to this one.

1099
01:10:01,600 --> 01:10:06,880
So GRPO, you use advantages
that are a result of this group

1100
01:10:06,880 --> 01:10:08,240
computation.

1101
01:10:08,240 --> 01:10:11,120
But then PPO, you
have an advantage

1102
01:10:11,120 --> 01:10:17,440
that is a result of rewards
and the value function,

1103
01:10:17,440 --> 01:10:20,800
which is per token.

1104
01:10:20,800 --> 01:10:24,000
Yeah?

1105
01:10:26,400 --> 01:10:29,280
So what are the
models at stake here?

1106
01:10:29,280 --> 01:10:31,200
So here, we have
some models that we

1107
01:10:31,200 --> 01:10:33,680
use that are, quote
unquote, frozen,

1108
01:10:33,680 --> 01:10:36,160
that are not the
ones that we train.

1109
01:10:36,160 --> 01:10:38,880
So for GRPO, we have
the reference model

1110
01:10:38,880 --> 01:10:41,440
that we do the KL divergence on.

1111
01:10:41,440 --> 01:10:44,400
And then we have
the reward model,

1112
01:10:44,400 --> 01:10:47,600
which we trained in the past.

1113
01:10:47,600 --> 01:10:52,480
And the same is
the case for PPO.

1114
01:10:52,480 --> 01:10:58,400
Now, one thing to note is
that in the reasoning case,

1115
01:10:58,400 --> 01:11:00,560
we are actually not
training a reward

1116
01:11:00,560 --> 01:11:04,400
model because we know how to
tell whether a solution is

1117
01:11:04,400 --> 01:11:05,920
correct or not.

1118
01:11:05,920 --> 01:11:08,640
We actually have a
verifiable reward.

1119
01:11:08,640 --> 01:11:11,440
So in the reasoning
case, we're actually

1120
01:11:11,440 --> 01:11:13,840
not having any
reward model at all.

1121
01:11:13,840 --> 01:11:16,800
It's the same for both.

1122
01:11:16,800 --> 01:11:21,440
Now what is different is
the models that we train.

1123
01:11:21,440 --> 01:11:27,280
So in the GRPO case, we
only train the policy model,

1124
01:11:27,280 --> 01:11:31,600
whereas in the PPO case,
we train the policy model

1125
01:11:31,600 --> 01:11:36,400
and the value function
the value model.

1126
01:11:36,400 --> 01:11:40,640
And this is the key difference.

1127
01:11:40,640 --> 01:11:47,440
So until now, we've seen only
drawings and illustrations.

1128
01:11:47,440 --> 01:11:49,920
So let's see some math.

1129
01:11:49,920 --> 01:11:54,080
So you have the GRPO
loss function at the top

1130
01:11:54,080 --> 01:11:57,200
and the PPO loss
function at the bottom.

1131
01:11:57,200 --> 01:11:59,360
They look scary.

1132
01:11:59,360 --> 01:12:04,320
But we're going to see
together some similarities

1133
01:12:04,320 --> 01:12:07,600
and some differences.

1134
01:12:07,600 --> 01:12:10,400
So what is one similarity?

1135
01:12:11,040 --> 01:12:15,360
Both of them, they
operate on the ratio

1136
01:12:15,360 --> 01:12:18,240
of the probability
of the current policy

1137
01:12:18,240 --> 01:12:22,880
and the probability
of the old policy.

1138
01:12:22,880 --> 01:12:25,920
So as the first point in common.

1139
01:12:26,800 --> 01:12:31,600
The second point in common
is that both of them, they

1140
01:12:31,600 --> 01:12:40,720
try to keep the updates within
some region, not too wide.

1141
01:12:40,720 --> 01:12:43,440
And they do that with
the clipping mechanism

1142
01:12:43,440 --> 01:12:47,120
that we saw last lecture.

1143
01:12:47,120 --> 01:12:49,840
So I recommend that you
just go through these charts

1144
01:12:49,840 --> 01:12:51,680
that we saw together.

1145
01:12:51,680 --> 01:12:56,080
When the advantage is positive,
how the loss looks like.

1146
01:12:56,080 --> 01:12:58,960
And when the
advantage is negative.

1147
01:12:58,960 --> 01:13:02,320
So this clipping
function just allows

1148
01:13:02,320 --> 01:13:08,880
you to not make updates that
are too big, that are too wide.

1149
01:13:08,880 --> 01:13:09,600
But now.

1150
01:13:09,600 --> 01:13:11,600
What is different.

1151
01:13:11,600 --> 01:13:16,800
So in the JPO case,
the KL divergence

1152
01:13:16,800 --> 01:13:19,120
is actually something
that is explicitly

1153
01:13:19,120 --> 01:13:24,240
part of the objective function.

1154
01:13:24,240 --> 01:13:28,240
Whereas for the PPO
case, this KL divergence

1155
01:13:28,240 --> 01:13:32,160
is typically part
of the advantage.

1156
01:13:32,160 --> 01:13:34,240
So this is more of
a technical detail.

1157
01:13:34,240 --> 01:13:38,080
But a few minutes
ago I had mentioned

1158
01:13:38,080 --> 01:13:42,240
that from an
implementation standpoint,

1159
01:13:42,240 --> 01:13:46,080
we typically incorporate
the KL divergence

1160
01:13:46,080 --> 01:13:49,760
within the rewards that are
considered in the advantage

1161
01:13:49,760 --> 01:13:51,520
computation.

1162
01:13:51,520 --> 01:13:54,560
So that's one difference.

1163
01:13:54,560 --> 01:13:56,240
And then the second
difference is

1164
01:13:56,240 --> 01:13:58,880
the way we compute advantages.

1165
01:13:58,880 --> 01:14:04,720
So we saw that GRPO,
we typically compute

1166
01:14:04,720 --> 01:14:06,720
rewards for each
completions, and then we

1167
01:14:06,720 --> 01:14:09,680
compare them with the other
completions from the group.

1168
01:14:09,680 --> 01:14:17,840
Whereas for PPO, we use the
rewards and the value models.

1169
01:14:17,840 --> 01:14:20,800
So far so good?

1170
01:14:20,800 --> 01:14:23,920
I think I have some other
things I want to talk about.

1171
01:14:23,920 --> 01:14:26,880
But before that, I just
want to open the floor

1172
01:14:26,880 --> 01:14:29,040
if anyone has any questions.

1173
01:14:29,040 --> 01:14:30,960
This is very
technical, by the way.

1174
01:14:30,960 --> 01:14:34,560
Very technical, probably the
hardest part of the whole class.

1175
01:14:34,560 --> 01:14:37,520
So it's completely
normal to, I guess,

1176
01:14:37,520 --> 01:14:39,840
take some time to digest that.

1177
01:14:39,840 --> 01:14:43,600
And if no one has any questions,
I actually see this as more

1178
01:14:43,600 --> 01:14:46,720
of an alarm for myself
because this is maybe--

1179
01:14:47,680 --> 01:14:48,960
I don't know.

1180
01:14:48,960 --> 01:14:54,080
So let me if there's
any questions on this.

1181
01:14:54,080 --> 01:15:00,640
And yeah, absolutely no problem
to have any kind of questions.

1182
01:15:00,640 --> 01:15:06,080
Is everything super clear?

1183
01:15:06,080 --> 01:15:06,880
Super clear?

1184
01:15:07,440 --> 01:15:12,880
So just tell yourself
that these algorithms,

1185
01:15:12,880 --> 01:15:18,080
they're just there to tune
your model in the RL stage.

1186
01:15:18,800 --> 01:15:23,680
PPO is heavily used in the
preference tuning framework,

1187
01:15:23,680 --> 01:15:27,360
where you try to tune
your model to align it

1188
01:15:27,360 --> 01:15:30,960
with human preferences,
and is commonly

1189
01:15:30,960 --> 01:15:36,000
used for these reasoning
based training.

1190
01:15:36,000 --> 01:15:38,320
So I think if you tell
yourself that is something.

1191
01:15:38,320 --> 01:15:39,520
And then the second
thing you need

1192
01:15:39,520 --> 01:15:46,560
to tell yourself is GRPO differs
from PPO in that GRPO does not

1193
01:15:46,560 --> 01:15:49,280
need a value function.

1194
01:15:49,280 --> 01:15:52,560
It actually computes
its advantages

1195
01:15:52,560 --> 01:15:58,320
by comparing the rewards with
respect to other completions.

1196
01:15:58,320 --> 01:16:01,840
And then the PPO, it
takes in the reward,

1197
01:16:01,840 --> 01:16:03,760
it takes in the value,
and then compares

1198
01:16:03,760 --> 01:16:08,320
the two to get the advantage.

1199
01:16:08,320 --> 01:16:10,960
So if this is making sense,
I think this is already

1200
01:16:10,960 --> 01:16:13,120
a very good thing.

1201
01:16:13,120 --> 01:16:16,080
So is this making sense?

1202
01:16:16,080 --> 01:16:17,200
Yeah?

1203
01:16:20,000 --> 01:16:23,040
I would also recommend to
just rewatch the recording.

1204
01:16:23,040 --> 01:16:24,400
So we're recording this.

1205
