1208
01:16:36,720 --> 01:16:42,000
And what we're going to
see now is some extensions

1209
01:16:42,000 --> 01:16:47,600
of the GRPO work that was done
last year that people have

1210
01:16:47,600 --> 01:16:50,240
done in the past few months.

1211
01:16:50,240 --> 01:16:53,840
So this research is
going back to early 2025,

1212
01:16:53,840 --> 01:16:57,200
but it has gained
enough traction for us

1213
01:16:57,200 --> 01:16:59,600
to talk about it in this class.

1214
01:17:00,480 --> 01:17:02,800
So if you remember
what I mentioned

1215
01:17:02,800 --> 01:17:07,920
in the beginning of the
lecture, reasoning tokens

1216
01:17:07,920 --> 01:17:11,280
are being charged
to you as a user.

1217
01:17:11,280 --> 01:17:15,760
So you don't want to pay a lot.

1218
01:17:15,760 --> 01:17:17,600
You don't want to pay too much.

1219
01:17:17,600 --> 01:17:21,200
So you want your model
to do what you want,

1220
01:17:21,200 --> 01:17:23,840
but you do not want it to
generate too much so that you're

1221
01:17:23,840 --> 01:17:26,480
getting charged for it.

1222
01:17:26,480 --> 01:17:28,800
And also from the
provider side, I

1223
01:17:28,800 --> 01:17:31,760
guess it's much better
to be more efficient.

1224
01:17:31,760 --> 01:17:34,880
So there is an
incentive to see what

1225
01:17:34,880 --> 01:17:40,960
we can optimize from the
output length perspective.

1226
01:17:40,960 --> 01:17:45,280
So if you see the
training of these models,

1227
01:17:45,280 --> 01:17:50,320
one thing that you notice
is that as you train it

1228
01:17:50,320 --> 01:17:56,720
in the RL stage, the
output increases in length.

1229
01:17:56,720 --> 01:18:01,920
So here this graph shows as
a function of the RL step

1230
01:18:01,920 --> 01:18:04,960
the average length per response.

