you want to think about,

1472
01:33:36,640 --> 01:33:42,560
just do it, but put
it into think boxes.

1473
01:33:42,560 --> 01:33:45,600
And then once you're
ready to give your answer,

1474
01:33:45,600 --> 01:33:49,680
you should wrap it
under like an answer--

1475
01:33:51,360 --> 01:33:55,680
basically your answer blocks.

1476
01:33:55,680 --> 01:33:58,720
And what you see here
in red is what you

1477
01:33:58,720 --> 01:34:02,000
replace by the sample prompts.

1478
01:34:02,960 --> 01:34:06,560
And then at the end,
you give the opportunity

1479
01:34:06,560 --> 01:34:09,440
to the model to respond.

1480
01:34:09,440 --> 01:34:11,600
Does that make sense?

1481
01:34:11,600 --> 01:34:13,280
OK, great.

1482
01:34:13,280 --> 01:34:15,040
And I'm going to
show you, again,

1483
01:34:15,040 --> 01:34:16,800
a graph that Afshine had shown.

1484
01:34:16,800 --> 01:34:21,600
So it was done on R1-Zero
where they said that

1485
01:34:21,600 --> 01:34:25,040
without any prior
supervision, just having

1486
01:34:25,040 --> 01:34:30,000
these as a reward increases
scores on reasoning based

1487
01:34:30,000 --> 01:34:30,640
benchmarks.

1488
01:34:30,640 --> 01:34:33,040
So this one I think is on AIM.

1489
01:34:33,040 --> 01:34:34,560
This like math one.

1490
01:34:34,560 --> 01:34:40,240
And you see that the
accuracy improves over time.

1491
01:34:40,240 --> 01:34:45,040
And you might think, all is
solved, it's great, no SFT,

1492
01:34:45,040 --> 01:34:48,080
and we already have the
best performance possible.

1493
01:34:48,080 --> 01:34:52,640
Well, not so easy,
because the authors,

1494
01:34:52,640 --> 01:34:55,120
when they looked at
the reasoning chains,

1495
01:34:55,120 --> 01:34:58,960
they saw some issues
with it of two kinds.

1496
01:34:58,960 --> 01:35:02,320
So first, when the model
was thinking about--

1497
01:35:03,440 --> 01:35:06,480
was emitting distinct
tokens, sometimes it

1498
01:35:06,480 --> 01:35:08,720
would mix languages.

1499
01:35:08,720 --> 01:35:11,920
And you had also syntax issues.

1500
01:35:11,920 --> 01:35:14,320
And you could
hypothesize that this

1501
01:35:14,320 --> 01:35:16,800
might be the case because
you haven't really

1502
01:35:16,800 --> 01:35:20,480
seen any strong supervision
just before that.

1503
01:35:20,480 --> 01:35:23,200
And you give the
opportunity to the model

1504
01:35:23,200 --> 01:35:29,840
to optimize anything it wants,
but it doesn't really have,

1505
01:35:30,560 --> 01:35:35,040
as a background, a strong
supervision signal to anchor on.

1506
01:35:35,040 --> 01:35:37,920
So this is one key
challenge that we're

1507
01:35:37,920 --> 01:35:43,200
going to see together, how
they try to resolve it.

1508
01:35:43,200 --> 01:35:49,840
Does the R1-Zero
process make sense?

1509
01:35:49,840 --> 01:35:51,200
Awesome.

1510
01:35:51,200 --> 01:35:54,080
So now that we have
seen what R1-Zero

1511
01:35:54,080 --> 01:35:57,680
tried to prove, the
fact that with RL only,

1512
01:35:57,680 --> 01:36:00,560
you can get reasoning
level performance,

1513
01:36:00,560 --> 01:36:04,080
now we're going to see how to
adjust the challenges that we

1514
01:36:04,080 --> 01:36:07,840
have seen into a full pipeline.

1515
01:36:07,840 --> 01:36:10,720
So that one, they call it R1.

1516
01:36:10,720 --> 01:36:13,920
And they start from
the same basis.

1517
01:36:13,920 --> 01:36:16,720
So they start from
a V3 base, which

1518
01:36:16,720 --> 01:36:20,560
is the pre-trained model
that's DeepSeek had

1519
01:36:20,560 --> 01:36:22,560
trained during their V3 paper.

1520
01:36:22,560 --> 01:36:27,440
So it was the non-reasoning
version of this model.

1521
01:36:27,440 --> 01:36:29,040
So they start from it.

1522
01:36:29,040 --> 01:36:32,000
And then instead of
starting directly

1523
01:36:32,000 --> 01:36:36,800
to doing the RL stage
that we have discussed,

1524
01:36:36,800 --> 01:36:39,360
they try to align
it in a way that

1525
01:36:39,360 --> 01:36:44,880
will nicely try to alleviate
the issues we have seen.

1526
01:36:44,880 --> 01:36:50,560
So it starts from what they
called as cold start data.

1527
01:36:50,560 --> 01:36:55,200
They generated CoTs.

1528
01:36:57,120 --> 01:36:58,880
during the R1-Zero stage.

1529
01:36:58,880 --> 01:37:02,320
And these CoTs
sometimes had issues.

1530
01:37:02,320 --> 01:37:06,560
So they used humans to
rewrite some of these

1531
01:37:06,560 --> 01:37:09,360
so that all these CoTs
are compliant when

1532
01:37:09,360 --> 01:37:13,680
it comes to formatting
language consistency.

1533
01:37:13,680 --> 01:37:16,880
And then they used
these pairs, prompts

1534
01:37:16,880 --> 01:37:25,040
and then rewritten prompts,
as data to train SFT on it.

1535
01:37:26,800 --> 01:37:31,840
And I think there was no number
given on the number of samples

1536
01:37:31,840 --> 01:37:33,520
given to that stage.

1537
01:37:33,520 --> 01:37:35,920
But from the wording
of the paper,

1538
01:37:35,920 --> 01:37:37,760
it could have been
several orders

1539
01:37:37,760 --> 01:37:40,560
of magnitude less than
some of the other stages

1540
01:37:40,560 --> 01:37:41,360
that we have seen.

1541
01:37:41,360 --> 01:37:46,480
So potentially in the
[INAUDIBLE] case of input output

1542
01:37:46,480 --> 01:37:48,880
pairs.

1543
01:37:48,880 --> 01:37:52,560
So now that we have
this stage ready,

1544
01:37:52,560 --> 01:37:58,400
they continued with the RL
stage that R1 0 would do.

1545
01:37:58,400 --> 01:38:03,120
And then we're going to
explore the reward function

1546
01:38:03,120 --> 01:38:04,080
that they used.

1547
01:38:04,080 --> 01:38:08,640
So not only we have
these verifiable reward

1548
01:38:08,640 --> 01:38:13,680
based on the response of
the reasoning model output

1549
01:38:13,680 --> 01:38:18,960
that we wanted to have, but also
we have the formatting reward.

1550
01:38:18,960 --> 01:38:22,320
And there is something new
that they introduced as well

1551
01:38:22,320 --> 01:38:26,160
to counter the effects of
having poor readability

1552
01:38:26,160 --> 01:38:28,960
in their thoughts.

1553
01:38:28,960 --> 01:38:32,560
There was something called a
language consistency reward

1554
01:38:32,560 --> 01:38:38,080
where they use a
very simple heuristic

1555
01:38:38,080 --> 01:38:43,600
to assess whether the model
indeed doesn't mix languages.

1556
01:38:43,600 --> 01:38:47,440
So I believe it was the ratio
of the tokens in the target

1557
01:38:47,440 --> 01:38:49,760
language in the outputted chain.

1558
01:38:49,760 --> 01:38:53,520
So they just put that in
order to maximize the amount

1559
01:38:53,520 --> 01:38:58,080
of correct language tokens.

1560
01:39:00,800 --> 01:39:02,000
Great.

1561
01:39:02,000 --> 01:39:06,160
And after this first
pass of RL, they

1562
01:39:06,160 --> 01:39:12,000
continued on with SFT with
a very interesting strategy.

1563
01:39:12,000 --> 01:39:15,760
So they do it as a larger
scale than the cold start one.

1564
01:39:15,760 --> 01:39:20,960
And now they mix both reasoning
and non-reasoning data

1565
01:39:20,960 --> 01:39:25,200
in order to make the model
useful to the span of cases

1566
01:39:25,200 --> 01:39:30,400
that you as a user might
solicitate the model for.

1567
01:39:30,400 --> 01:39:33,840
And regarding
non-reasoning data,

1568
01:39:33,840 --> 01:39:37,120
they recycled some
of the data that

1569
01:39:37,120 --> 01:39:42,080
was used for their non-reasoning
version of the model for V3.

1570
01:39:42,080 --> 01:39:44,560
So about 200k pairs.

1571
01:39:44,560 --> 01:39:47,120
And it covers the
domains that we

1572
01:39:47,120 --> 01:39:50,800
have mentioned during the
instruction tuning lecture.

1573
01:39:50,800 --> 01:39:54,400
So like a broad array of topics.

1574
01:39:54,400 --> 01:39:56,080
And then what they
did is that they

1575
01:39:56,080 --> 01:40:02,000
added to it a lot of pairs that
are directed towards reasoning.

1576
01:40:02,000 --> 01:40:04,800
So the ratio was 3 to 1.

1577
01:40:04,800 --> 01:40:12,080
And then the reasoning ones were
generating with a method called

1578
01:40:12,080 --> 01:40:13,840
rejection sampling.

1579
01:40:13,840 --> 01:40:17,600
So what they did
is that they took

1580
01:40:17,600 --> 01:40:23,040
some prompts covering these
reasoning-based fields,

1581
01:40:23,040 --> 01:40:25,680
and they used the model
that had been trained

1582
01:40:25,680 --> 01:40:28,800
so far to generate a response.

1583
01:40:28,800 --> 01:40:33,200
And then based on the
output and with some judge,

1584
01:40:33,200 --> 01:40:36,880
they would keep some answers
and reject others such

1585
01:40:36,880 --> 01:40:41,760
that the resulting data sets
would be of very high quality.

1586
01:40:41,760 --> 01:40:44,560
So this is what they call
by rejection sampling.

1587
01:40:44,560 --> 01:40:50,480
It's just the fact of
filtering out any answers that

1588
01:40:50,480 --> 01:40:52,800
are not perfect.

1589
01:40:52,800 --> 01:40:56,480
And the reason why I guess
they did it automatically

1590
01:40:56,480 --> 01:41:01,440
with some LLM judges and so on
is given the scale of the data--

1591
01:41:01,440 --> 01:41:08,640
and these were heuristics that
worked pretty nice on that--

1592
01:41:08,640 --> 01:41:10,160
you had a question?

1593
01:41:10,160 --> 01:41:11,440
No?

1594
01:41:13,520 --> 01:41:17,200
So once they were
done with that,

1595
01:41:17,200 --> 01:41:20,880
they went on to
a last stage that

1596
01:41:20,880 --> 01:41:25,120
was one that might
make you think

1597
01:41:25,120 --> 01:41:29,200
about the ones that occur in
non-reasoning model training

1598
01:41:29,200 --> 01:41:30,880
pipelines.

1599
01:41:30,880 --> 01:41:34,560
So they mix this time
not only reasoning data,

1600
01:41:34,560 --> 01:41:36,640
but also non-reasoning ones.

1601
01:41:36,640 --> 01:41:40,960
So for the reasoning data, same
kind of reward as we have seen.

1602
01:41:40,960 --> 01:41:44,800
But on the
non-reasoning one, you

1603
01:41:44,800 --> 01:41:48,480
try to align the model
on characteristics

1604
01:41:48,480 --> 01:41:53,600
that make an LLM a helpful
assistant and a harmless one.

1605
01:41:53,600 --> 01:41:58,240
So you have this helpfulness
and harmlessness components

1606
01:41:58,240 --> 01:42:01,200
of that part of the reward.

1607
01:42:01,200 --> 01:42:03,840
And the harmlessness
was a reward

1608
01:42:03,840 --> 01:42:09,200
that was applied on the whole
tokens that were outputted.

1609
01:42:09,200 --> 01:42:11,120
So not just the
output because you

1610
01:42:11,120 --> 01:42:16,240
want the chain of thoughts in
the think section of the answer

1611
01:42:17,760 --> 01:42:19,840
to be harmless indeed.

1612
01:42:19,840 --> 01:42:23,200
And then the helpfulness
one was more focused

1613
01:42:23,200 --> 01:42:28,400
on what you saw
at the user level.

1614
01:42:28,400 --> 01:42:29,920
OK, great.

1615
01:42:29,920 --> 01:42:32,640
And just to give some
idea of the results

1616
01:42:32,640 --> 01:42:37,280
they got, so first,
you notice that

1617
01:42:40,000 --> 01:42:42,400
on reasoning-based
benchmarks you

1618
01:42:42,400 --> 01:42:44,960
have two clusters of
results that appear.

1619
01:42:44,960 --> 01:42:47,600
You have all these non
reasoning based models

1620
01:42:47,600 --> 01:42:49,680
that have some performance.

1621
01:42:49,680 --> 01:42:51,920
And then the
reasoning-based ones

1622
01:42:51,920 --> 01:42:58,880
have unsurprisingly a
performance that is much higher.

1623
01:42:58,880 --> 01:43:01,840
And then the second thing that
we observe out of these results

1624
01:43:01,840 --> 01:43:06,480
is that R1 was pretty
competitive with respect

1625
01:43:06,480 --> 01:43:10,000
to closed source models that
claim to be reasoning-based.

1626
01:43:10,000 --> 01:43:15,120
And it was a pretty
interesting moments,

1627
01:43:15,120 --> 01:43:17,920
as Afshine had
mentioned, to reproduce

1628
01:43:19,520 --> 01:43:24,000
such a level of performance.

1629
01:43:24,000 --> 01:43:25,600
OK, great.

1630
01:43:25,600 --> 01:43:30,240
So I want to finish this
lecture on an interesting note

1631
01:43:30,240 --> 01:43:36,640
of let's say you don't have
a 600B MOE at your disposal.

1632
01:43:36,640 --> 01:43:37,920
Let's say you have
a smaller model,

1633
01:43:37,920 --> 01:43:39,920
but you want to have
the capabilities

1634
01:43:39,920 --> 01:43:43,840
of these large reasoning model.

1635
01:43:43,840 --> 01:43:45,840
How would you go about it?

1636
01:43:45,840 --> 01:43:49,040
So I just want to give
you a reminder of how

1637
01:43:49,040 --> 01:43:53,920
we had dealt with this topic
a few lectures ago when

1638
01:43:53,920 --> 01:43:54,880
we talked about distillation.

1639
01:43:55,840 --> 01:43:59,280
So at that time, we were just
talking about pre-training

1640
01:43:59,280 --> 01:44:03,440
and an instruction tuning where
the data we were dealing with

1641
01:44:03,440 --> 01:44:04,480
was fixed.

1642
01:44:04,480 --> 01:44:06,320
So for example, for
next token prediction,

1643
01:44:06,320 --> 01:44:10,000
you know the text you
want the model to fit on.

1644
01:44:10,000 --> 01:44:12,080
For SFT, you have fixed pairs.

1645
01:44:12,080 --> 01:44:14,400
You know exactly what
you want to learn.

1646
01:44:14,400 --> 01:44:20,240
And what you did was look for
each next token prediction

1647
01:44:20,240 --> 01:44:25,280
at the output probability
distribution of a teacher model.

1648
01:44:25,280 --> 01:44:27,840
And on your student
model, instead

1649
01:44:27,840 --> 01:44:32,000
of fitting a hard label
of the next token,

1650
01:44:32,000 --> 01:44:35,600
you fit it instead the whole
probability distribution

1651
01:44:35,600 --> 01:44:39,360
of the teacher model
in order to distill

1652
01:44:39,360 --> 01:44:44,720
the knowledge of that teacher
model into the student model.

1653
01:44:44,720 --> 01:44:47,600
You all remember that?

1654
01:44:47,600 --> 01:44:49,440
Yeah?

1655
01:44:49,440 --> 01:44:54,640
So now how could you go
ahead with this in this case?

1656
01:44:54,640 --> 01:44:57,200
So here, as you have
seen, we don't necessarily

1657
01:44:57,200 --> 01:45:02,320
have SFT pairs based on
reasoning out of the box.

1658
01:45:02,320 --> 01:45:06,080
So if you want to distill the
knowledge of a teacher model

1659
01:45:06,080 --> 01:45:09,520
here, the authors have gone
through an interesting route

1660
01:45:09,520 --> 01:45:11,120
that is still
called distillation,

1661
01:45:11,120 --> 01:45:13,680
but it's another flavor of it.

1662
01:45:13,680 --> 01:45:18,160
So we use the teacher
model here, R1,

1663
01:45:18,160 --> 01:45:22,880
to generate some sample
responses including

1664
01:45:23,680 --> 01:45:25,840
thinking tokens.

1665
01:45:25,840 --> 01:45:29,280
So this is something
that is done offline.

1666
01:45:29,280 --> 01:45:33,520
And then in a second
stage, you run this SFT

1667
01:45:33,520 --> 01:45:37,920
and fit a smaller
model on your distilled

1668
01:45:38,960 --> 01:45:43,440
model, which is typically much
less weights than the teacher

1669
01:45:43,440 --> 01:45:44,400
one.

1670
01:45:44,400 --> 01:45:47,680
So instead of fitting a
probability distribution

1671
01:45:47,680 --> 01:45:51,840
over the next token, you
just fit the entire sequence.

1672
01:45:51,840 --> 01:45:54,880
You just try to predict
the same sequence of tokens

1673
01:45:54,880 --> 01:45:59,600
that the teacher has outputted.

1674
01:45:59,600 --> 01:46:04,400
Does this framing of
distillation here make sense?

1675
01:46:04,400 --> 01:46:06,560
Yeah?

1676
01:46:06,560 --> 01:46:07,440
Awesome.

1677
01:46:07,440 --> 01:46:11,520
And I'm going to conclude here
by looking at the results.

1678
01:46:11,520 --> 01:46:14,400
So you can see that the
results, once again,

1679
01:46:14,400 --> 01:46:19,280
are very competitive with
closed source alternatives that

1680
01:46:19,280 --> 01:46:23,440
claim to be a smaller
version of a reasoning model.

1681
01:46:23,440 --> 01:46:25,840
So for example,
o1-mini, you can see

1682
01:46:25,840 --> 01:46:28,000
that the numbers here are
competitive with respect

1683
01:46:28,000 --> 01:46:29,360
to that.

1684
01:46:29,360 --> 01:46:32,320
And then you could also
wonder, but why did you

1685
01:46:32,320 --> 01:46:38,720
go through the trouble of just
distilling when you could just

1686
01:46:38,720 --> 01:46:41,280
do the same RL techniques.

1687
01:46:41,280 --> 01:46:48,240
Well, actually, the authors
have seen that at a smaller size

1688
01:46:48,240 --> 01:46:51,760
level, distilling
the knowledge is

1689
01:46:51,760 --> 01:46:54,400
more efficient in
terms of performance

1690
01:46:54,400 --> 01:46:57,920
than directly
learning from scratch.

1691
01:46:59,600 --> 01:47:02,400
All good?

1692
01:47:02,400 --> 01:47:07,360
And with that, have
a great weekend.